1)  Upon Successful Connection:
    SHH, Port 22 is commonly used by clients to connect to remote systems via SSH, providing command-line interface access. 
    After successfully verifying authentication, users can gain secure access to the full capabilities of the remote system, 
    allowing them to execute commands, transfer files, and manage the system as needed.

2) By default, 
   user computers and organization servers keep port 22 closed unless they explicitly need remote access capabilities.
   Keeping port 22 closed is a security measure that helps prevent unauthorized SSH access and limits exposure to potential attacks.


